    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Previous names",
            "shortText": "<p><i>Rhus glauca</i></p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_9_9788",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Sprawling shrub, sometimes becoming a small multi-stemmed tree. Branches characteristically angular with pale grey bark. Leaves compound, with a distinctive blueish hue, glossy, but sometimes with resinous coating that dries to a grey powdery layer. Each leaf made up of three sessile leaflets, the central one being the largest, tips of leaves slightly indented with a small central spike. Delicate sprays of minute greenish-white or yellow flowers are followed by clusters of small spherical berries in female plants. These are initially green, becoming chestnut brown in summer and dry to black in autumn.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_9789",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Typically height 1-3 m tall, but can form small trees up to 4 m. Flower spays about 50 mm across. Berries 3 mm diameter.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_9790",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Zimbabwe, Mozambique and South Africa.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Along the coast from Velddrif on the West Coast to Eastern Cape, but also widespread inland.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_9791",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Common both inland and along the coast. Tolerant to drought, salt-spray and high wind and an important pioneer species. Leaves have a resinous smell when crushed. Pollinated by insects. This and other <i>Searsia</i> species are food plants for a variety of butterfly larvae. Birds eat the ripe berries and help disperse the seeds.</p><p>Is used as a garden plant, especially in coastal gardens subject to harsh dry conditions. The fruit are edible but sour and can be fermented to make traditional beer. Branches of female plants in berry are sometimes used in flower arrangements.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_9792",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Photosynthetic.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_9793",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>There are separate male and female plants<strong>. </strong>Flowers in late winter with berries in female plants most abundant in summer.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_9794",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>There are many other easily-confused regional species in this genus.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_9795",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        }
    ],
